67
00:03:28,415 --> 00:03:31,400
A spectator can be found in so many different and several places.

68
00:03:31,760 --> 00:03:38,363
A spectator can be someone watching a stream without any action, just being there and watching a streamer.

69
00:03:38,363 --> 00:03:45,186
But it can be also someone who is really involved and really engaged, constantly interacting with the streamer

70
00:03:45,186 --> 00:03:50,049
and with other spectators through the chat, for example, asking questions, making comments.

71
00:03:50,689 --> 00:03:58,312
It can be also someone who is just sitting at home, maybe a parent watching over the shoulder of the child playing a video game,

72
00:03:58,312 --> 00:04:00,913
maybe being invested, maybe not at all.

73
00:04:00,913 --> 00:04:08,996
But it could be also a fan in a stadium filled with thousands of fans enjoying together a StarCraft play.

74
00:04:09,517 --> 00:04:15,301
So spectators can be found in so many several places and we also need to consider the different

75
00:04:15,301 --> 00:04:21,226
types of spectators with different backgrounds. For this talk we want to use a definition of

76
00:04:21,226 --> 00:04:27,291
spectators, that spectators are basically people who follow the gameplay in real time without being

77
00:04:27,291 --> 00:04:32,575
the main player in the game. Eventually they have impact on the game to some extent which

78
00:04:32,575 --> 00:04:34,576
we'll hear later but it's not the main focus.

79
00:04:35,961 --> 00:04:41,322
But first let us take a step back and see what is important for the player.

80
00:04:41,322 --> 00:04:46,384
So the player wants to have a good playing and streaming experience.

81
00:04:46,384 --> 00:04:54,186
And a player wants interaction possibilities with the viewers that are there in the chat or viewing on site for example.

82
00:04:54,766 --> 00:04:59,829
It's all about entertaining those viewers and retaining those viewers.

83
00:04:59,829 --> 00:05:05,573
And in the end, the goal is to build a community around the game, the player, and the stream, for example.

84
00:05:06,222 --> 00:05:09,024
When you design a video game for a spectator, however,

85
00:05:09,024 --> 00:05:11,026
you need to think of different aspects.

86
00:05:11,026 --> 00:05:13,588
Because as soon as a player would enter a stream,

87
00:05:13,588 --> 00:05:16,850
the spectator must immediately know what's going on,

88
00:05:16,850 --> 00:05:19,212
understand the gameplay mechanics, and so on.

89
00:05:19,212 --> 00:05:22,414
You should think of different interaction possibilities

90
00:05:22,414 --> 00:05:25,176
with either the player or with the other viewers.

91
00:05:25,176 --> 00:05:27,778
They want to be entertained, surprised,

92
00:05:27,778 --> 00:05:30,300
so they have different motives for coming to the stream.

93
00:05:30,300 --> 00:05:32,202
Or they just want to be part of the community

94
00:05:32,202 --> 00:05:33,483
as a social aspect.

95
00:05:34,522 --> 00:05:35,678
need to know that.

96
00:05:36,472 --> 00:05:39,214
Fans and spectators is something different.

97
00:05:39,214 --> 00:05:44,438
A fan can become to a, a spectator can become to a fan,

98
00:05:44,438 --> 00:05:47,481
but they don't start off as a fan immediately.

99
00:05:47,481 --> 00:05:51,164
So fans are usually motivated by a lot of achievements.

100
00:05:51,164 --> 00:05:53,506
However, a spectator can be motivated

101
00:05:53,506 --> 00:05:55,748
by so many different things

102
00:05:55,748 --> 00:05:59,151
without the necessity that they are fans.

103
00:05:59,151 --> 00:06:01,573
They can just enjoy the aesthetics of the game,

104
00:06:01,573 --> 00:06:04,616
this drama or the skill of players.

105
00:06:05,116 --> 00:06:11,798
There are different strategies which are definitely interesting for us as game designers,

106
00:06:11,798 --> 00:06:15,340
how to make views to fans, but that's probably a different talk.

107
00:06:15,340 --> 00:06:21,282
Today we want to focus on the motives for the spectators and what's interesting about that.

108
00:06:23,341 --> 00:06:31,183
Spectators are motivated by different aspects of a streaming or game watching experience.

109
00:06:31,183 --> 00:06:37,045
So some are eventually more interested in the game itself, some are eventually interested in

110
00:06:37,045 --> 00:06:45,547
the streamer or player or team, esports team, as a person or as a team, and others are interested

111
00:06:45,547 --> 00:06:51,128
in the social experiences and want to interact with other spectators or the community.

112
00:06:51,789 --> 00:06:56,497
So, in literature we can find different motives for spectating.

113
00:06:56,497 --> 00:07:03,670
Interestingly enough, there's not a lot of research yet on streaming or in eSports behavior.

114
00:07:03,670 --> 00:07:04,051
It's...

115
00:07:04,556 --> 00:07:06,978
growing and becoming more important.

116
00:07:06,978 --> 00:07:09,100
But the most research we found,

117
00:07:09,100 --> 00:07:12,323
and which is very similar to what we're interested in,

118
00:07:12,323 --> 00:07:14,645
can be found in sports events.

119
00:07:14,645 --> 00:07:18,048
So going to a football game, to a soccer game, for example,

120
00:07:18,048 --> 00:07:21,031
and understanding the spectator's motives there

121
00:07:21,031 --> 00:07:23,393
can help us also understand the motives

122
00:07:23,393 --> 00:07:26,576
for people watching a stream or going to an e-sports mat.

123
00:07:27,728 --> 00:07:30,891
So some of the motives can be, for example,

124
00:07:30,891 --> 00:07:33,393
the identification, that a spectator really

125
00:07:33,393 --> 00:07:36,135
wants to be associated with a successful player

126
00:07:36,135 --> 00:07:39,977
and also wants to celebrate the success.

127
00:07:39,977 --> 00:07:42,719
The aesthetics, this is really, really important.

128
00:07:42,719 --> 00:07:46,122
They really enjoy the beauty of the game.

129
00:07:47,563 --> 00:07:54,725
we have drama and excitement. This is this idea that you experience this thrill, maybe stress,

130
00:07:54,725 --> 00:08:02,708
but a very pleasant form of stress while watching a game. Escape. Escape would be that you escape

131
00:08:02,708 --> 00:08:09,751
from this daily routine and you come home from work and you just turn on a stream and watch the

132
00:08:09,751 --> 00:08:12,051
stream just to getting relaxed again.

133
00:08:12,987 --> 00:08:17,911
Knowledge. Eventually you're a gamer yourself and you want to learn more about the game.

134
00:08:17,911 --> 00:08:25,256
You want to experience through the skills of the player and you want to learn the social interactions.

135
00:08:25,256 --> 00:08:31,200
Especially on Twitch this is so important that you're able to communicate with other spectators.

136
00:08:31,200 --> 00:08:34,103
This relation to some sort of a community, to some sort of a group.

137
00:08:34,103 --> 00:08:36,785
And then the team or the player support.

138
00:08:36,785 --> 00:08:40,307
That you're part of a community who is supporting a player.

139
00:08:41,678 --> 00:08:45,382
Similar to player types, which all of you might know,

140
00:08:45,382 --> 00:08:47,765
there are also different types of spectators.

141
00:08:47,765 --> 00:08:51,229
This is one simple model we built,

142
00:08:51,229 --> 00:08:54,132
where you have the player and the game

143
00:08:54,132 --> 00:08:56,355
as main interest points for spectators.

144
00:08:56,355 --> 00:08:58,337
Could be also other spectators.

145
00:08:58,337 --> 00:09:00,900
And some people really want to interact.

146
00:09:01,080 --> 00:09:03,542
Some, however, want to consume.

147
00:09:03,542 --> 00:09:06,984
So those, for example, who want to interact with other players

148
00:09:06,984 --> 00:09:09,846
or with the players are socializers.

149
00:09:09,846 --> 00:09:13,048
Those who want to consume and learn from the skills

150
00:09:13,048 --> 00:09:15,510
from a player, for example, can be learners.

151
00:09:15,510 --> 00:09:18,472
Those who want to be part of the game,

152
00:09:18,472 --> 00:09:22,095
make some sort of impact on the game, can be participators.

153
00:09:22,095 --> 00:09:24,377
And those who are consuming the games,

154
00:09:24,377 --> 00:09:26,198
they're just enjoying the beauty.

155
00:09:26,899 --> 00:09:32,501
And based on that, in literature, we find nine different personas.

156
00:09:32,501 --> 00:09:37,623
And what we all know, when we create games, it's always important to think about those

157
00:09:37,623 --> 00:09:40,864
different personas who we are designing the games for.

158
00:09:40,864 --> 00:09:42,505
Same can be done for spectators.

159
00:09:43,365 --> 00:09:49,192
So there's for example the bystander. The bystander is someone who is still not very

160
00:09:49,192 --> 00:09:55,200
interested in the game yet, who just happens to be there. This one is either uninformed about the

161
00:09:55,200 --> 00:10:00,726
game or uninvested and not really engaged yet. However this can change.

162
00:10:01,267 --> 00:10:06,591
If there's something happening which is engaging, for example some drama or some excitement,

163
00:10:06,591 --> 00:10:14,518
this one can become to a curious one. The curious is suddenly interested in the game and then wants

164
00:10:14,518 --> 00:10:20,763
to learn more about the game. It starts with a small fascination and they eventually start

165
00:10:20,763 --> 00:10:26,749
watching and watching more and this one eventually becomes to the inspired. The inspired

166
00:10:28,046 --> 00:10:30,027
feels like, oh, that's a cool game.

167
00:10:30,027 --> 00:10:32,227
I also want to play this game.

168
00:10:32,227 --> 00:10:34,748
This one would eventually, after the stream,

169
00:10:34,748 --> 00:10:38,289
go to Steam and buy the game him or herself.

170
00:10:38,289 --> 00:10:42,090
This is already a very, very nice process

171
00:10:42,090 --> 00:10:43,351
when he got too inspired.

172
00:10:44,031 --> 00:10:49,274
And as soon as you already know about the game, you eventually become the pupil.

173
00:10:49,274 --> 00:10:54,537
A pupil, this one wants to learn. This one wants to understand specific techniques,

174
00:10:54,537 --> 00:10:58,559
tricks of the player, or wants to learn about specific maps within the game.

175
00:10:58,559 --> 00:11:06,644
He's or she's very interested in learning details, so this one would ask questions,

176
00:11:06,644 --> 00:11:11,006
would interact with the player, or would interact with other spectators.

177
00:11:11,701 --> 00:11:15,482
And then there's the unsatisfied, AKA the grumpy one,

178
00:11:15,482 --> 00:11:19,423
who'd rather like to be playing him or herself,

179
00:11:19,423 --> 00:11:20,504
which comes from a desire.

180
00:11:20,504 --> 00:11:24,865
An example for that would be a dad playing with his son,

181
00:11:24,865 --> 00:11:27,726
and the son wants to play and the dad has to watch,

182
00:11:27,726 --> 00:11:29,186
but actually wants to play himself.

183
00:11:29,827 --> 00:11:36,417
Next, there's the entertained and the entertained would rather prefer watching over playing.

184
00:11:36,417 --> 00:11:43,128
So, there's this difference that content is being watched for entertainment basically like a movie.

185
00:11:43,983 --> 00:11:45,283
Then we have the assistant.

186
00:11:45,283 --> 00:11:49,804
The assistant wants to sort of impact the game progress.

187
00:11:49,804 --> 00:11:53,505
They want to help, they want to be some sort of advisor.

188
00:11:53,505 --> 00:11:55,766
This one would be, for example,

189
00:11:55,766 --> 00:11:58,107
all the brothers sitting next to me

190
00:11:58,107 --> 00:12:00,227
and trying to help me through the levels.

191
00:12:00,227 --> 00:12:02,408
But this could be also someone

192
00:12:02,408 --> 00:12:04,909
who wants to tell me about things

193
00:12:04,909 --> 00:12:06,689
which I don't want to know

194
00:12:06,689 --> 00:12:08,530
because I want to explore the game myself.

195
00:12:09,903 --> 00:12:11,784
Then there's the commentator.

196
00:12:11,784 --> 00:12:13,826
This is a very interesting one.

197
00:12:13,826 --> 00:12:17,749
This one is a spectator and a performer or entertainer

198
00:12:17,749 --> 00:12:18,630
at the same time.

199
00:12:18,630 --> 00:12:21,432
This one wants to entertain other spectators.

200
00:12:21,432 --> 00:12:24,194
This one would be constantly talking about the game,

201
00:12:24,194 --> 00:12:27,457
giving comments, in the chat, in the Twitch chat,

202
00:12:27,457 --> 00:12:30,099
also constantly talking about the game.

203
00:12:30,099 --> 00:12:32,180
This can be some sort of a cameraman

204
00:12:32,180 --> 00:12:33,341
telling a different perspective.

205
00:12:35,070 --> 00:12:38,190
And last, the last one is a part of the crowd.

206
00:12:38,190 --> 00:12:41,851
This one wants to be part of the community.

207
00:12:41,851 --> 00:12:44,032
If something insane is happening

208
00:12:44,032 --> 00:12:48,233
and the crowd would go wild or in a stream,

209
00:12:48,233 --> 00:12:51,494
the entire chat will be flooded.

210
00:12:51,494 --> 00:12:54,835
This is what the part of the crowd would enjoy.

211
00:12:56,676 --> 00:13:03,488
Yeah, so now that we've learned about these different types of personas, of spectators,

212
00:13:03,488 --> 00:13:06,854
how can we design to engage the spectators?

213
00:13:07,700 --> 00:13:11,322
Well, first of all, our main goal as a game designer

214
00:13:11,322 --> 00:13:13,363
would be to create a playable game.

215
00:13:13,363 --> 00:13:15,605
But speaking of spectators, we also

216
00:13:15,605 --> 00:13:17,966
want to create a watchable game.

217
00:13:17,966 --> 00:13:21,388
So that means viewers need to be able to understand what's

218
00:13:21,388 --> 00:13:23,830
going on in the game, and they need

219
00:13:23,830 --> 00:13:26,692
to be able to keep track of everything that is going on

220
00:13:26,692 --> 00:13:28,213
in the game at any time.

221
00:13:28,213 --> 00:13:30,334
And also, we want to retain those viewers.

222
00:13:30,334 --> 00:13:33,876
That means we want them to come back to our stream

223
00:13:33,876 --> 00:13:35,317
or to our play session.

224
00:13:35,317 --> 00:13:36,818
And they should keep watching.

225
00:13:37,800 --> 00:13:43,586
What we identified were those three phases of spectator engagement.

226
00:13:43,586 --> 00:13:50,212
First, we want to attract people to a game or to a stream, and we want to teach them about the game.

227
00:13:50,212 --> 00:13:54,276
So, what is the game about? How is the game played? What are the rules of the game?

228
00:13:55,367 --> 00:14:02,189
Next, we want to retain those viewers so that they come back and maybe tell others and watch again,

229
00:14:02,189 --> 00:14:10,711
keep watching. And third, we want community involvement and engagement. So that means

230
00:14:10,711 --> 00:14:14,873
we want people to interact with streamers and with each other.

231
00:14:15,513 --> 00:14:20,257
And this is all to support the spectator's motives that we have heard before.

232
00:14:20,257 --> 00:14:24,281
So, for example, we can attract with the aesthetics of a game,

233
00:14:24,281 --> 00:14:28,585
or with drama, or just with basic simplicity,

234
00:14:28,585 --> 00:14:33,050
so that people know how the game works.

235
00:14:33,730 --> 00:14:40,032
And we can use drama for retaining viewers, for example, and we can try to build up knowledge

236
00:14:40,032 --> 00:14:46,815
so that people come back, learn something more. And then we have social interaction for involvement

237
00:14:46,815 --> 00:14:53,737
and engagement. We can encourage people to teach others about the game and we can support this

238
00:14:53,737 --> 00:15:01,139
affiliation that viewers will be supporting a specific team, for example, or a special player

239
00:15:01,139 --> 00:15:02,820
or a stream. So...

240
00:15:03,935 --> 00:15:07,877
What happens when a viewer walks into a stream?

241
00:15:07,877 --> 00:15:11,259
First question that pops up is, what is happening here?

242
00:15:11,259 --> 00:15:14,601
And as I said before, the optimum thing

