00:15:14,601 --> 00:15:19,484
would be that the game is just very easy to pick up.

244
00:15:19,484 --> 00:15:23,106
And from the very first second, you actually

245
00:15:23,106 --> 00:15:23,866
know what's going on.

246
00:15:23,866 --> 00:15:27,549
But we want to have viewers learn about the game

247
00:15:27,549 --> 00:15:29,610
while watching the game or the stream.

248
00:15:30,490 --> 00:15:39,076
So, our goal is first to design to attract viewers, and that should be seen in all the

249
00:15:39,076 --> 00:15:45,020
different kind of areas of development of the game. Coming from game design, then graphics,

250
00:15:45,020 --> 00:15:46,501
UI, all those features.

251
00:15:46,882 --> 00:15:51,443
They should give spectators visual hints and experiences

252
00:15:51,443 --> 00:15:53,484
about all the actions that are currently

253
00:15:53,484 --> 00:15:54,864
happening in the game.

254
00:15:54,864 --> 00:15:57,685
People should know about the tactics and even emotions

255
00:15:57,685 --> 00:15:59,306
the players are going through.

256
00:15:59,306 --> 00:16:02,627
A good example for that is in League of Legends,

257
00:16:02,627 --> 00:16:04,847
there is a color scheme indicating

258
00:16:04,847 --> 00:16:06,608
what is happening at the time.

259
00:16:06,608 --> 00:16:08,809
So you just jump into a stream, and then you

260
00:16:08,809 --> 00:16:10,169
see a certain color, and you know, OK,

261
00:16:10,169 --> 00:16:12,650
this is the current phase, or this is maybe

262
00:16:12,650 --> 00:16:13,950
what's going on at the moment.

263
00:16:14,391 --> 00:16:22,482
And people or viewers should understand the current situation of the game, for example, if the team is winning or losing.

264
00:16:23,898 --> 00:16:26,719
Next, we want to design to teach viewers.

265
00:16:26,719 --> 00:16:31,942
This is an example we did in one of our games at Rarebyte.

266
00:16:31,942 --> 00:16:38,605
There's a difference between UI done for players

267
00:16:38,605 --> 00:16:40,946
versus UI for spectators.

268
00:16:40,946 --> 00:16:43,027
So for a player, it's maybe important

269
00:16:43,027 --> 00:16:45,728
to really focus on the player's character

270
00:16:45,728 --> 00:16:47,729
and see what's going on with the character

271
00:16:47,729 --> 00:16:50,610
and around the character and give a lot of feedback there.

272
00:16:50,610 --> 00:16:51,571
But for spectators,

273
00:16:52,251 --> 00:16:57,304
Maybe they want an overview of all the players in multiplayer and they want to be able to

274
00:16:57,304 --> 00:17:00,090
compare player skills or player stats.

275
00:17:02,677 --> 00:17:09,101
One element which is very exciting here is one method called information asymmetry.

276
00:17:09,101 --> 00:17:15,946
Here the idea is that the player and the spectator have different pieces of information.

277
00:17:15,946 --> 00:17:22,490
A very obvious one as a streamer or as a player, I do know for example what strategy I'm planning at the moment.

278
00:17:22,490 --> 00:17:26,613
This is just in my head, so obviously this is something I as a player know, but the spectator doesn't.

279
00:17:26,613 --> 00:17:29,635
I as a streamer can now decide whether or not it makes my stream more interesting,

280
00:17:29,635 --> 00:17:31,897
or whether or not it makes my stream more interesting.

281
00:17:32,137 --> 00:17:36,098
to tell the spectators this piece of information

282
00:17:36,098 --> 00:17:40,559
or to keep it for myself to keep the spectators

283
00:17:40,559 --> 00:17:44,200
full of tension and excitement what's happening next.

284
00:17:44,200 --> 00:17:46,500
So keep this element of surprise.

285
00:17:46,500 --> 00:17:49,581
As a game designer, I can also add elements

286
00:17:49,581 --> 00:17:50,921
to make this happen.

287
00:17:50,921 --> 00:17:52,241
For example, what we just heard,

288
00:17:52,241 --> 00:17:56,042
to add specific UI elements or give specific overviews

289
00:17:56,042 --> 00:17:58,843
which are just seen by a spectator.

290
00:17:59,343 --> 00:18:01,704
So for example, I can see an entire map

291
00:18:01,704 --> 00:18:05,246
of all the different players competing to each other,

292
00:18:05,246 --> 00:18:08,388
and I know what's going on, but the players do not.

293
00:18:08,388 --> 00:18:11,169
So this is also helping me to get excited.

294
00:18:11,169 --> 00:18:12,930
Or I know as a spectator,

295
00:18:12,930 --> 00:18:14,591
there's a specific trap over there,

296
00:18:14,591 --> 00:18:16,952
and the player is just running over there.

297
00:18:16,952 --> 00:18:19,793
And I, as a spectator, get very excited about that.

298
00:18:21,210 --> 00:18:25,292
So why do viewers stay or come back to a game or stream?

299
00:18:25,292 --> 00:18:28,013
Well, first, there's just this fierce competition

300
00:18:28,013 --> 00:18:29,493
that you know from sports.

301
00:18:29,493 --> 00:18:33,035
People like to see competition and see teams or players

302
00:18:33,035 --> 00:18:36,577
competing and basically playing against each other.

303
00:18:36,577 --> 00:18:38,818
And then there is drama, of course.

304
00:18:38,818 --> 00:18:40,798
You never know who's going to win this game.

305
00:18:40,798 --> 00:18:41,579
Is it this player?

306
00:18:41,579 --> 00:18:42,299
Is it this team?

307
00:18:42,299 --> 00:18:42,959
Is it another one?

308
00:18:43,660 --> 00:18:55,468
And then there's this affiliation that we want to support, that viewers get engaged and will support their favorite streamer, performer, player or team.

309
00:18:55,468 --> 00:18:59,411
What we want to do is, we want to design for drama.

310
00:18:59,411 --> 00:19:06,536
So we want to create an intense playthrough and intense matches to support that drama.

311
00:19:06,536 --> 00:19:08,438
And if you think of esports, that's...

312
00:19:09,435 --> 00:19:16,463
Basically what is happening there is that players that are very similar in skill play

313
00:19:16,463 --> 00:19:17,183
against each other.

314
00:19:17,183 --> 00:19:21,207
So there's a natural drama coming from that.

315
00:19:21,207 --> 00:19:27,234
But if you have games that are played by just random players, this is different.

316
00:19:27,234 --> 00:19:33,120
And maybe you have to think about integrating mechanics to rebalance different player skills.

317
00:19:33,260 --> 00:19:38,021
There's this infamous example of rubber banding in Mario Kart,

318
00:19:38,021 --> 00:19:41,281
where you can basically, if you fall behind, you can catch up

319
00:19:41,281 --> 00:19:44,582
because you just get faster.

320
00:19:44,582 --> 00:19:47,602
We even used that in a hoverboard racing game.

321
00:19:47,602 --> 00:19:51,723
You just had to, like, move onto a trail

322
00:19:51,723 --> 00:19:53,403
and then you were able to catch up

323
00:19:53,403 --> 00:19:56,144
and there was just an intense race coming from that

324
00:19:56,144 --> 00:20:01,545
with completely different kind of players or skilled players.

325
00:20:02,943 --> 00:20:06,824
Also, we want to design to create the unexpected.

326
00:20:06,824 --> 00:20:11,545
So a viewer comes to stream and should never know exactly

327
00:20:11,545 --> 00:20:12,366
what will happen next.

328
00:20:12,366 --> 00:20:16,367
And that's one of the reasons this viewer will probably

329
00:20:16,367 --> 00:20:18,188
stay to find out.

330
00:20:18,188 --> 00:20:22,229
We can add random events or story twists to our games

331
00:20:22,229 --> 00:20:24,790
to change this kind of balance within the game.

332
00:20:24,790 --> 00:20:29,051
We can add surprise boxes, crates, or loot to do that.

333
00:20:29,591 --> 00:20:32,394
For example, this here is from We Are Screwed,

334
00:20:32,394 --> 00:20:34,135
a game we're currently working on.

335
00:20:34,135 --> 00:20:37,619
We have procedural content generation

336
00:20:37,619 --> 00:20:40,521
and random events in that game.

337
00:20:40,521 --> 00:20:42,483
And it's a space co-op game

338
00:20:42,483 --> 00:20:44,365
where people take on different roles.

339
00:20:44,365 --> 00:20:47,468
And we use this, kind of, those random elements

340
00:20:47,468 --> 00:20:50,190
to force people to change roles all the time.

341
00:20:52,750 --> 00:21:00,817
Something which is also very interesting is how to make it happen that viewers can be part of the experience.

342
00:21:00,817 --> 00:21:08,824
So there could be, for example, a passive mechanic to give streamers the option to involve

343
00:21:09,464 --> 00:21:11,585
the spectators in the game.

344
00:21:11,585 --> 00:21:15,626
So for example, what I use in Darkest Dungeon,

345
00:21:15,626 --> 00:21:17,747
there's this option that you have those different

346
00:21:17,747 --> 00:21:19,287
characters which you can play,

347
00:21:19,287 --> 00:21:20,787
and I would always look at the stream

348
00:21:20,787 --> 00:21:22,208
and look who's most active,

349
00:21:22,208 --> 00:21:25,249
and then I would name the in-game characters

350
00:21:25,249 --> 00:21:28,170
based on my spectators, based on my viewers.

351
00:21:28,170 --> 00:21:30,790
So this is, they're basically getting involved

352
00:21:30,790 --> 00:21:34,291
in a very passive way, but I as a player,

353
00:21:34,291 --> 00:21:37,352
I have the mechanic to involve them.

354
00:21:37,352 --> 00:21:38,133
On the other hand.

355
00:21:39,000 --> 00:21:45,423
being as a spectator active in a game experience can be also very engaging.

356
00:21:45,423 --> 00:21:53,206
This would mean that spectators can vote for specific things happening in the game,

357
00:21:53,206 --> 00:21:57,888
or now it becomes increasingly interesting to also make mechanics that you can for example

358
00:21:57,888 --> 00:22:03,531
cheer for specific players within a game, and then they get a specific boost in the game as a game

359
00:22:03,531 --> 00:22:05,012
mechanic or a specific item.

360
00:22:06,592 --> 00:22:09,575
In the end, it's about building a community around the game

361
00:22:09,575 --> 00:22:12,657
and making it accessible to all those viewers,

362
00:22:12,657 --> 00:22:15,019
all those different kind of spectator personas.

363
00:22:15,019 --> 00:22:18,302
The audience should feel welcome at all times,

364
00:22:18,302 --> 00:22:21,565
while players should still feel safe.

365
00:22:21,565 --> 00:22:25,067
And the goal is to let viewers be a part of something.

366
00:22:27,510 --> 00:22:36,966
Next, we want to go, or quickly go through some strategies we used on our projects. So first...

367
00:22:38,104 --> 00:22:41,427
So there's so many evaluation strategies.

368
00:22:41,427 --> 00:22:44,130
I mean, coming from a UX background,

369
00:22:44,130 --> 00:22:46,493
there are so many ways how you can think

370
00:22:46,493 --> 00:22:48,935
of evaluating the player experience,

371
00:22:48,935 --> 00:22:50,957
and all those can be also used, basically,

372
00:22:50,957 --> 00:22:52,979
to evaluate the spectator's experience.

373
00:22:52,979 --> 00:22:55,001
Those can be things like observations,

374
00:22:55,001 --> 00:22:58,124
think-out-loud tests, working with data,

375
00:22:58,124 --> 00:23:01,107
in-game data, in-game metrics, interviews, you name it.

376
00:23:01,628 --> 00:23:07,696
But we want to introduce two specific models which we used in our collaboration basically.

377
00:23:07,696 --> 00:23:11,802
And the first one is the in this point of view.

378
00:23:12,067 --> 00:23:13,889
Yeah, let's start with the indie point of view.

379
00:23:13,889 --> 00:23:16,111
And of course, this is called the party test.

380
00:23:16,111 --> 00:23:18,534
And it looks exactly like in this picture here.

381
00:23:18,534 --> 00:23:22,298
This works in a way, and this is very simple.

382
00:23:22,298 --> 00:23:25,180
We would just invite 15 to 20 people to our office

383
00:23:25,180 --> 00:23:28,544
and do something called a play party.

384
00:23:28,544 --> 00:23:31,587
And we would just start a game

385
00:23:31,587 --> 00:23:33,709
and then have some people play this game.

386
00:23:34,370 --> 00:23:37,332
and other people watch those people play.

387
00:23:37,332 --> 00:23:41,516
And then we evaluate and we record that

388
00:23:41,516 --> 00:23:44,259
and we collect data basically.

389
00:23:44,259 --> 00:23:47,161
And we can identify issues like with onboarding,

390
00:23:47,161 --> 00:23:49,704
with usability and playability.

391
00:23:49,704 --> 00:23:52,086
And this is both for player

392
00:23:52,086 --> 00:23:54,608
and spectator engagement and experience.

393
00:23:56,634 --> 00:23:59,015
And my point, the academics point of view,

394
00:23:59,015 --> 00:24:01,376
I love, again, I love working with data.

395
00:24:01,376 --> 00:24:03,837
And I do a lot of big data analysis,

396
00:24:03,837 --> 00:24:06,177
so I really try to gather a lot of data,

397
00:24:06,177 --> 00:24:11,199
either qualitative or quantitative data.

398
00:24:11,199 --> 00:24:14,300
But what's very interesting is, for example,

399
00:24:14,300 --> 00:24:18,622
to build different models based on the interactions

400
00:24:18,622 --> 00:24:22,063
of spectators with the game, or with the stream,

401
00:24:22,063 --> 00:24:25,004
with the player, or with other spectators.

402
00:24:25,704 --> 00:24:29,665
This can be usually, can be data locked in the game,

403
00:24:29,665 --> 00:24:32,606
can be locked in the stream, can be Twitch data,

404
00:24:32,606 --> 00:24:33,987
or can be even Twitter data,

405
00:24:33,987 --> 00:24:35,587
which is just related to the game.

406
00:24:35,587 --> 00:24:39,869
I want to introduce you to models which we use,

407
00:24:39,869 --> 00:24:41,969
or two processes we often use.

408
00:24:41,969 --> 00:24:45,270
The first one is graph-based analysis.

409
00:24:45,270 --> 00:24:48,812
Here we built, based on the interaction of the spectators

410
00:24:48,812 --> 00:24:51,993
with each other or with the player, we built a graph.

411
00:24:51,993 --> 00:24:54,533
This means if as soon as two.

412
00:24:54,834 --> 00:24:59,936
spectators would interact in a chat at a very similar time. We assume this might be some sort

413
00:24:59,936 --> 00:25:05,758
of communication, so we would make a connection between two nodes within this graph, which means

414
00:25:05,758 --> 00:25:12,161
okay they're connected, they have some sort of relationship within this graph, and we can make

415
00:25:12,161 --> 00:25:13,661
sense out of this data.

416
00:25:14,102 --> 00:25:19,285
So, looking at a lot of data, this could be a graph, this is how such a graph looks like.

417
00:25:19,285 --> 00:25:26,390
And what we can see, there are some nodes with a lot of connections. Those nodes could be very

418
00:25:26,390 --> 00:25:33,694
relevant and important points to look at. Those can be, for example, those personas of commentators

419
00:25:33,694 --> 00:25:37,036
who want to entertain the others and are really important.

420
00:25:37,577 --> 00:25:39,738
as an engagement starting point.

421
00:25:39,738 --> 00:25:44,341
So, can we use this information to give those a specific reward, for example,

422
00:25:44,341 --> 00:25:50,864
to make sure to keep them engaged and keep them in our stream or part of our game experience?

423
00:25:50,864 --> 00:25:56,707
And then we can also identify the weaker points, those with not a lot of connections.

424
00:25:56,707 --> 00:26:02,791
And we can think of ways how to integrate those and help them to connect to other spectators.

425
00:26:03,976 --> 00:26:08,517
On the other hand, this is one of the more traditional ways to do data analysis.

426
00:26:08,517 --> 00:26:14,318
This is basically where you look at the number of interactions over time.

427
00:26:14,318 --> 00:26:20,760
So this is when you look at the Twitch chat, for example, you can see in minute 40,

428
00:26:20,760 --> 00:26:24,760
there was something going on, something very important was going on.

429
00:26:24,760 --> 00:26:30,042
And we can find out by looking at the in-game data, here was a specific boss fight.

430
00:26:30,042 --> 00:26:32,202
Apparently also the streamer did something very well.

431
00:26:32,622 --> 00:26:37,085
Can we use this information to make the engagement even better for the next stream?

432
00:26:37,085 --> 00:26:46,512
So just to summarize, we can also say that those different relations strategies can actually work

433
00:26:46,512 --> 00:26:51,936
together. Again, so that I can do my data analysis, I need a lot of data.

434
00:26:52,516 --> 00:27:01,082
The point is that very, very often when we work with studios, it's becoming very expensive and

435
00:27:01,082 --> 00:27:07,907
it's becoming very complicated because the data the studio locked in the game just was not right,

436
00:27:07,907 --> 00:27:11,650
was not locked in a correct way or just not locked at all.

437
00:27:12,570 --> 00:27:19,675
Yeah, and the idea is just to work together from the very beginning of the project and do a data definition together.

438
00:27:19,675 --> 00:27:28,661
And then we as a studio would take this definition and build it right into the very foundation of the game.

439
00:27:28,661 --> 00:27:31,183
And we then plan and prototype our game.

440
00:27:31,183 --> 00:27:35,626
And when a build is ready of the game, we would start a play testing session.

441
00:27:35,626 --> 00:27:41,870
And then we would be able to collect data that is then given back to the research institution.

442
00:27:42,442 --> 00:27:45,824
And since the data already fits what we sort of need,

443
00:27:45,824 --> 00:27:48,066
because of this definition phase,

444
00:27:48,066 --> 00:27:50,949
for us it's so much easier and much more cost-effective

445
00:27:50,949 --> 00:27:54,332
to make sense out of the data and help the studio,

446
00:27:54,332 --> 00:27:57,534
even if it's a small studio or a big studio,

